{"id":"p001-c01","type":"text","source":"manual","content":"# BF-3 Flanger — Owner's Manual\n\n[User note: 2017 Roland product, English-market version. I dialed in this pedal for the chorus chunk in Creep.]\n\nBefore using this unit, carefully read the sections entitled: \"USING THE UNIT SAFELY\" and \"IMPORTANT NOTES\" (supplied on a separate sheet).\n\nAfter reading, keep the document(s) where it will be available for immediate reference.","provenance":{"manual":"BF-3_M_eng03_W.pdf","page":1,"rough_region":"top","scraped_at":"2026-05-11T18:30:00Z"},"_user_edited":true}
{"id":"p001-c02","type":"image","source":"manual","content":{"image_category":"panel-diagram","description":"Panel Descriptions diagram. Center: a top-down close-up of the BF-3's top panel showing five knobs labeled (left to right) MANUAL, RES (resonance), DEPTH, RATE, and MODE; a small round CHECK indicator LED above the knob row; and the MODE knob positions labeled ULTRA, STANDARD, GATE/PAN, MOMENTARY around its rotation. The pedal body shows a 'BF-3 Flanger' faceplate in teal/blue. Surrounding the pedal: a stack of AC adaptor + power illustration on the upper-left (callout 1 = AC adaptor, marked 'PSA series, sold separately'); on the right side, two source illustrations of an Electric Guitar (top) and Bass Guitar (bottom) connected by cable to the pedal; on the lower-left, two stacked amplifier illustrations labeled Guitar Amplifier and Bass Amplifier connected to the output jacks. Red numbered callouts 1–12 point at: (1) AC adaptor connection, (2) the CHECK indicator LED, (3) the OUTPUT A (MONO) jack on the left side and OUTPUT B jack, (4) the GUITAR IN jack on the right side, (5) the BASS IN jack on the right side, (6) the pedal footswitch on the front, (7) the thumbscrew at the front edge of the pedal, (8) the MANUAL knob, (9) the RES knob, (10) the DEPTH knob, (11) the RATE knob, (12) the MODE knob. The illustration ties each callout to the legend tables below."},"provenance":{"manual":"BF-3_M_eng03_W.pdf","page":1,"rough_region":"top","scraped_at":"2026-05-11T18:30:00Z"}}
{"id":"p001-c03","type":"text","source":"manual","content":"## Panel Descriptions — legend\n\n**1. DC IN jack** — Accepts connection of an AC Adaptor (PSA series; sold separately). By using an AC Adaptor, you can play without being concerned about how much battery power you have left.\n* As soon as you connect the AC adaptor, the unit is turned on.\n* We recommend that you keep batteries installed in the unit even though you'll be powering it with the AC adaptor. That way, you'll be able to continue a performance even if the cord of the AC adaptor gets accidentally disconnected from the AC adaptor.\n* Use only the specified AC adaptor (PSA-series).\n* If the AC adaptor is connected while power is on, the power supply is drawn from the AC adaptor.\n\n**2. CHECK indicator** — This indicator shows whether an effect is ON/OFF, indicates the tempo (TEMPO mode), and also doubles as the Battery Check indicator. The indicator lights when an effect is ON.\n* If this indicator goes dim or no longer lights while an effect is ON or while the BF-3 is in TEMPO mode, the battery is near exhaustion and should be replaced immediately. → \"Changing the Battery\"\n\n**3. OUTPUT jacks A (MONO), B** — The output jacks are used to connect the unit to an amplifier or another effects unit. For mono use, make the connection to the OUTPUT A (MONO) jack.\n\n**4. GUITAR IN jack** — This jack accepts input signals coming from a guitar, some other musical instrument, or another effects unit.\n\n**5. BASS IN jack** — This jack accepts input signal coming from a bass guitar.\n* BASS IN is disabled when the GUITAR IN jack is used.\n\n* The GUITAR IN and BASS IN jacks double as power switches. Power to the unit is turned on when you plug into the GUITAR IN or BASS IN jack; the power is turned off when the cable is unplugged. Be sure to disconnect any cord plugged into the GUITAR IN or BASS IN jack when not using this effects device.\n\n**6. Pedal switch** — Use this switch to turn the effect on/off or to input the tempo.\n* You cannot input the tempo in MOMENTARY mode.\n\n**7. Thumbscrew** — When this screw is loosened, the pedal will open, allowing you to change the battery. → \"Changing the Battery\"\n\n**8. [MANUAL] knob** — Adjusts the center frequency at which to apply the effect. The range is raised as you turn the knob to the right (clockwise).\n* The settings range varies with the selected mode, as well as when an instrument is connected to BASS IN.\n\n**9. [RES] knob** — Adjusts the amount of resonance (feedback). The more the knob is turned to the right, the more the flanger sound is emphasized, and the stronger the characteristic effect in the sound becomes.\n\n**10. [DEPTH] knob** — Adjusts the sweep depth. The effect deepens as you turn the knob to the right.\n* The MANUAL knob has no function when this knob is turned completely clockwise.\n\n**11. [RATE] knob** — Adjusts the rate of the flanging. The flange effect speeds up as you turn the knob to the right.\n\n**12. MODE knob** — Selects the flanger effect and pedal mode.\n  * **ULTRA** — Provides a stronger flanger effect than STANDARD.\n  * **STANDARD** — Provides a normal flanger effect.\n  * **GATE / PAN** — When playing in mono, this creates radical changes in the output volume. When playing in stereo, this alternately pans the output to the left and right, resulting in a flanger effect that imparts a sense of rotation or spinning.\n  * **MOMENTARY** — The flanger effect is applied only while the BF-3's pedal is depressed. The STANDARD tone is applied, and flanging starts in the low end.\n  * You cannot input the tempo in MOMENTARY mode.","provenance":{"manual":"BF-3_M_eng03_W.pdf","page":1,"rough_region":"top","scraped_at":"2026-05-11T18:30:00Z"}}
{"id":"p001-c04","type":"image","source":"manual","content":{"image_category":"panel-diagram","description":"Operating the Unit — small diagram. Top-down close-up of the BF-3's control panel (same layout as the main Panel Descriptions diagram) with red numbered callouts pointing at five controls: callout 5 = MANUAL knob (leftmost), callout 6 = RES knob, callout 4 = DEPTH knob (center), callout 3 = RATE knob, callout 2 = MODE knob (rightmost). The CHECK indicator is shown above the knob row. The numbering corresponds to the order of steps in the adjacent 'Operating the Unit' numbered list."},"provenance":{"manual":"BF-3_M_eng03_W.pdf","page":1,"rough_region":"middle","scraped_at":"2026-05-11T18:30:00Z"}}
{"id":"p001-c05","type":"text","source":"manual","content":"## Operating the Unit\n\n1. When you have made the necessary connections, depress the pedal switch to turn the effect on. (the CHECK indicator turns red.)\n   * When MOMENTARY mode is selected, continue pressing the pedal switch. (the effect is on only while the pedal is depressed).\n2. Select the mode with the [MODE] knob.\n   * When MOMENTARY is selected, the CHECK indicator light goes off, and the effect is switched off. Hold the pedal down when using the following settings in MOMENTARY mode (the effect is on only while the pedal is depressed).\n3. Set the flanging rate with the [RATE] knob.\n4. Set the sweep depth with the [DEPTH] knob.\n5. Set the center frequency to which the effect is applied with the [MANUAL] knob.\n6. Turn the [RES] knob to set the strength of the effect.","provenance":{"manual":"BF-3_M_eng03_W.pdf","page":1,"rough_region":"middle","scraped_at":"2026-05-11T18:30:00Z"}}
{"id":"p001-c06","type":"image","source":"manual","content":{"image_category":"panel-diagram","description":"State-transition table titled 'When Switching to Tempo Input with the Effect ON (CHECK indicator: Red)'. Four columns, each showing a device state. Row 1 (CHECK Indicator) shows icons: Red lit / Unlit / Red/Green Blinking / Red lit. Row 2 (Flanger Effects) shows text labels: ON / OFF / ON / ON. Row 3 (Pedal switch) shows four illustrations of a foot pedal in different press states with annotations: (state 1→2) 'Press and hold the BF-3's pedal switch for at least two seconds', (state 2→3) 'Press the BF-3's pedal switch in timing with the tempo', (state 3→4) 'Press and hold the BF-3's pedal switch for at least two seconds'. Row 4 (RATE) labels: 'Effect reflects knob positions' / (blank, effect off) / 'Effect synchronized to tempo' / 'Effect reflects knob positions'. The table shows how the pedal is double-tap-and-held to toggle into and out of tempo-input mode while the flanger effect remains audible.","_low_confidence_category":true},"provenance":{"manual":"BF-3_M_eng03_W.pdf","page":1,"rough_region":"middle","scraped_at":"2026-05-11T18:30:00Z"}}
{"id":"p001-c07","type":"image","source":"manual","content":{"image_category":"panel-diagram","description":"State-transition table titled 'When Switching to Tempo Input with the Effect OFF (CHECK indicator: Off)'. Same four-column shape as the Effect-ON variant. Row 1 (CHECK Indicator): Unlit / Red lit / Red/Green Blinking / Red lit. Row 2 (Flanger Effects): OFF / ON / ON / ON. Row 3 (Pedal switch) illustrations annotated: (state 1→2) 'Press and hold the BF-3's pedal switch for at least two seconds', (state 2→3) 'Press the BF-3's pedal switch in timing with the tempo', (state 3→4) 'Press and hold the BF-3's pedal switch for at least two seconds'. Row 4 (RATE): (blank) / 'Effect reflects knob positions' / 'Effect synchronized to tempo' / 'Effect reflects knob positions'. The variant starts from the effect-off state and reaches tempo-synced operation via the same long-press → tap → long-press sequence.","_low_confidence_category":true},"provenance":{"manual":"BF-3_M_eng03_W.pdf","page":1,"rough_region":"middle","scraped_at":"2026-05-11T18:30:00Z"}}
{"id":"p001-c08","type":"text","source":"manual","content":"### Setting the RATE by Inputting the Tempo with the Pedal Switch — notes\n\n* RATE cycles for use with the tempo settings can be made in the range of 0.1–18 seconds.\n* If you carry out Step 1 immediately after Step 2, Step 3 may inadvertently be interpreted as tempo input, thus changing the RATE setting. Allow a brief interval to pass before progressing from Step 2 to Step 3.\n* If you adjust the [RATE] knob after completing the settings, the effect then reflects the position of the [RATE] knob.\n* You cannot input the tempo in MOMENTARY mode.\n\n### Relationship Between the Flanger and Gate Effects\n\n* The gate effect switches on and off 32 times over the period of the flanger effect's rise and fall.\n* If you want to have the gate working on eighth notes, press the pedal switch at the beginning of the fifth measure of the song you want to have synchronized.","provenance":{"manual":"BF-3_M_eng03_W.pdf","page":1,"rough_region":"middle","scraped_at":"2026-05-11T18:30:00Z"}}
{"id":"p001-c09","type":"image","source":"manual","content":{"image_category":"parameter-envelope","description":"Flanger-and-Gate timing envelope chart. Vertical axis labeled 'Frequency' on the top half and 'GATE Effects' on the bottom half, both ranging 'Low' to 'High'. Horizontal axis labeled 'RATE' with time markers '16 Times' annotated four times across the width. Top curve: a triangular waveform with two peaks labeled 'Flanger Rise', 'Flanger Fall', 'Flanger Rise', 'Flanger Fall' — the flanger sweeps the frequency band up and down. Bottom row: a dense stripe of vertical bars showing the gate effect chopping on and off rapidly, with the legend 'GATE = ♪' (eighth-note) indicating the gate's clock division. Below the chart, two foot-pedal illustrations annotated 'Input the tempo' mark the start and end of the synchronized period, captioned 'Flanger Effects Rise' and 'Flanger Effects Fall'. The chart shows that the gate cycles 32 times over the flanger's rise-and-fall period, locked to the tapped tempo."},"provenance":{"manual":"BF-3_M_eng03_W.pdf","page":1,"rough_region":"middle","scraped_at":"2026-05-11T18:30:00Z"}}
{"id":"p001-c10","type":"text","source":"manual","content":"## Precautions When Connecting\n\n* To prevent malfunction and equipment failure, always turn down the volume, and turn off all the units before making any connections.\n* Once the connections have been completed, turn on power to your various devices in the order specified. By turning on devices in the wrong order, you risk causing malfunction and/or damage to speakers and other devices.\n  * **When powering up:** Turn on the power to your guitar amp last.\n  * **When powering down:** Turn off the power to your guitar amp first.\n* Before turning the unit on/off, always be sure to turn the volume down. Even with the volume turned down, you might hear some sound when switching the unit on/off. However, this is normal and does not indicate a malfunction.","provenance":{"manual":"BF-3_M_eng03_W.pdf","page":1,"rough_region":"middle","scraped_at":"2026-05-11T18:30:00Z"}}
{"id":"p001-c11","type":"image","source":"manual","content":{"image_category":"panel-diagram","description":"Changing the Battery — exploded-view-style diagram of the BF-3 with eight red numbered callouts. The illustration shows the pedal opened at the front edge with the battery housing visible. Callouts: (1) the thumbscrew at the front of the pedal, (2) the pedal flap that opens upward when the screw is loosened, (3) the battery housing inside the opened pedal, (4) the battery snap connector with red and black leads, (5) the coil spring inside the pedal compartment, (6) the spring base on the back of the pedal that the spring slips onto, (7) the path of the battery snap cord — flagged with a caution to avoid getting caught between the pedal coil, spring, and battery housing, (8) the guide bush hole that the thumbscrew is reinserted into to lock the pedal closed. To the right of the diagram, a labeled '9 V Battery' illustration. The exploded view is laid out vertically with the pedal body on the left and the loose battery + spring components on the right."},"provenance":{"manual":"BF-3_M_eng03_W.pdf","page":1,"rough_region":"bottom","scraped_at":"2026-05-11T18:30:00Z"}}
{"id":"p001-c12","type":"text","source":"manual","content":"## Changing the Battery\n\n1. Hold down the pedal and loosen the thumbscrew (1), then open the pedal (2) upward.\n   * The pedal can be opened without detaching the thumbscrew completely.\n2. Remove the old battery from the battery housing (3), and remove the battery snap (4) connected to it.\n3. Connect the battery snap to the new battery, and place the battery inside the battery housing.\n   * Be sure to carefully observe the battery's polarity (+ versus -).\n4. Slip the coil spring (5) onto the spring base (6) on the back of the pedal, and then close the pedal.\n   * Carefully avoid getting the battery snap cord (7) caught in the pedal coil, spring, and battery housing.\n5. Insert the thumbscrew into the guide bush hole (8) and tighten it securely.","provenance":{"manual":"BF-3_M_eng03_W.pdf","page":1,"rough_region":"bottom","scraped_at":"2026-05-11T18:30:00Z"}}
{"id":"p001-c13","type":"text","source":"manual","content":"## Main Specifications\n\n| Spec | Value |\n|---|---|\n| Nominal Input Level | -20 dBu |\n| Input Impedance | 1 MΩ |\n| Nominal Output Level | -20 dBu |\n| Output Impedance | 1 kΩ |\n| Recommended Load Impedance | 10 kΩ or greater |\n| Power Supply | Alkaline battery (9 V, 6LR61); AC adaptor (PSA series; sold separately) |\n| Current Draw | 60 mA. Expected battery life under continuous use: Alkaline: 4 hours. These figures will vary depending on the actual conditions of use. |\n| Dimensions | 73 (W) x 129 (D) x 59 (H) mm; 2-7/8 (W) x 5-1/8 (D) x 2-3/8 (H) inches |\n| Weight | 425 g / 15 oz (including Battery) |\n| Accessories | Leaflet (\"USING THE UNIT SAFELY\", \"IMPORTANT NOTES\" and \"Information\"); Alkaline battery (9 V, 6LR61) |\n| Options (sold separately) | AC adaptor: PSA series |\n\n* 0 dBu = 0.775 Vrms\n* This document explains the specifications of the product at the time that the document was issued. For the latest information, refer to the Roland website.\n\n## Use of Battery\n\n* The battery that was supplied with the unit is for temporary use, intended primarily for testing the unit's operation. We suggest replacing this with an alkaline dry cell.\n* If you handle batteries improperly, you risk explosion and fluid leakage. Make sure that you carefully observe all of the items related to batteries that are listed in \"USING THE UNIT SAFELY\" and \"IMPORTANT NOTES\" (supplied on a separate sheet).\n\n© 2017 Roland Corporation","provenance":{"manual":"BF-3_M_eng03_W.pdf","page":1,"rough_region":"bottom","scraped_at":"2026-05-11T18:30:00Z"}}
